snippet.textDisplay: look, Khusro was a muslim, sure. But he was born in Uttar Pradesh and raised in Delhi.  He was influenced by all of the cultures around him, both muslim and hindu.  As such, he uses allusions to both cultures in his poetry, because he wanted to speak to the common people, who were of both religions.  Just look at the images he uses - Jogis are obviously yogis and other mendicants, and the chaap tilak is a hindu symbol as well. The point is, his music belongs to all of us, and should be celebrated by hindus and muslims alike.
snippet.textOriginal: look, Khusro was a muslim, sure.
